                        <lb n="1"/>ταμυρααβεσακεδϙοιαϝεσ<persName type="attested"><name>ευρυμακες</name></persName>αγεπιποκεδλυτιμβε
                    </ab>
                </div>
                <div type="textpart" subtype="section" n="b">
                    <ab>    
                        <lb n="1"/>λεϝοπομανατεσεμαιδαρνακειβυρειταμομιαετιυρελα
                    </ab>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" subtype="transliteration" xml:lang="scx-Latn">                 
                <div type="textpart" subtype="section" n="a">
                    <ab>    
                        <lb n="1"/>tamuraabesakedqoiaveseurumakesagepipokedlutimbe
                    </ab>
                </div>
                <div type="textpart" subtype="section" n="b">
                    <ab>    
                        <lb n="1"/>levopomanatesemaidarnakeibureitamomiaetiurela
                    </ab>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app>
                        <note>Text after Martzloff 2011</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <div type="translation" subtype="version" n="1">
                    <p>[Martzloff's first hypothesis is that it is a ludic text involving one speaker talking to two interlocutors]</p>
                    <p>(Speaker to Interlocutor 1) [...] You are afar.Come closer, you who wish (sc. drinking)</p>
                    <p>(Speaker to Interlocutor 2) Eurymachus, come, thirsty, pass the jug (Speaker to Interlocutor 1)</p>
                    <p>(Speaker to Interlocutor 1) drink! </p>
                </div>
                <div type="translation" subtype="version" n="2">
                    <p>[Martzloff's second hypothesis is that it is a ludic text involving two speakers]</p>
                    <p>(Speaker1 to Speaker2) [...] You are afar, come closer, you who want to (sc. drink)</p>
                    <p>(Speaker2 to Speaker1) Come on, thirsty, pass the jug! / Come on, I drink, pass the jug</p>
                    <p>(Speaker1 to Speaker2) Drink!</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it">
                <div type="translation" subtype="version" n="1">
                    <p>(Speaker to Interlocutor 1) [...] Tu sei lontano. Avvicinati, tu che vuoi (sc. bere)</p>
                    <p>(Speaker to Interlocutor 2) Eurymachus, vieni, assetato, passa la brocca (Speaker to Interlocutor 1)</p>
                    <p>(Speaker to Interlocutor 1) Bevi!</p>
                </div>
                <div type="translation" subtype="version" n="2">
                    <p>(Speaker1 to Speaker2) [...] Tu sei lontano, avvicinati, tu che vuoi (sc. bere)</p>
                    <p>(Speaker2 to Speaker1) Dai, assetato, passa la brocca! / Dai, bevo, passa la brocca!</p>
                    <p>(Speaker1 to Speaker2) Bevi!</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" xml:lang="en" resp="#VM">
                <p/>
            </div>
